Refresh Cycle
The refresh cycle is the time interval between successive refresh operations for a DRAM row, typically set to 2ms.

Gate Capacitor
The gate capacitor in a DRAM cell stores electrical charge to represent binary data.

DRAM
DRAM (Dynamic Random-Access Memory) is a type of semiconductor memory that stores data using capacitors in storage cells, requiring periodic refresh to maintain data integrity.<SEP>DRAM is a type of volatile semiconductor memory with high density and lower cost, commonly used in computer main memory.

SRAM
SRAM (Static Random-Access Memory) is a type of semiconductor memory that stores data using flip-flops, does not require refreshing, and has faster access speeds than DRAM.<SEP>SRAM is a type of volatile semiconductor memory that is fast but more expensive and less dense than DRAM.<SEP>SRAM (Static Random Access Memory) is a type of memory used to implement TLB due to its high speed.<SEP>SRAM is a type of static random-access memory that uses bistable triggers to store information and maintains data without regeneration after reading.<SEP>SRAM (Static Random-Access Memory) is a type of memory technology used to build cache due to its speed and low latency.

1 to 2ms
The charge on a DRAM capacitor typically lasts only 1 to 2 milliseconds before needing refresh.

Storage Cell
The storage cell in DRAM consists of a single transistor and a capacitor, used to hold a single bit of data as electrical charge.<SEP>A storage cell, also known as a storage unit or storage element, is a physical device capable of maintaining two stable states to represent binary 0 and 1.<SEP>A storage cell is the basic building block of a memory system, consisting of a physical device that stores one binary bit.

Concentrated Refresh
Concentrated refresh is a method where all rows are refreshed consecutively within a single refresh interval, causing a temporary suspension of memory access.

Carbon-Fiber Spikes
Carbon-fiber spikes are advanced athletic footwear components but are not relevant to the DRAM context; this entity was mistakenly introduced and should be excluded.

Storage Matrix
The storage matrix, also referred to as the storage body or storage array, is the core structure of a memory system made up of interconnected storage cells.

Byte Addressing
Byte addressing is a method of organizing memory where each byte is assigned a unique address, commonly used in modern computers.

Main Memory
Main Memory, also known as RAM (Random Access Memory), primary memory, or main storage, is the primary repository for data and instructions actively used by a computer's central processing unit (CPU) during program execution. It serves as the principal storage component in a computer system, directly accessible by the CPU for rapid processing. Main Memory is implemented using DRAM (Dynamic Random Access Memory) chips and functions as the main workspace where programs and data are loaded for immediate access and manipulation. It is characterized by fast access speeds, higher cost per unit of storage, and relatively smaller capacity compared to secondary storage devices like hard drives or SSDs. As a volatile memory, Main Memory retains its contents only while the system is powered, losing all stored data upon shutdown or power interruption. It plays a critical role in supporting both cache and virtual memory operations, effectively bridging the speed gap between the CPU and slower secondary storage, thus enhancing overall system performance. The storage architecture of Main Memory is organized into a matrix of storage units, often partitioned into physical pages, enabling efficient data access, management, and alignment with the CPUâ€™s execution needs. Throughout software execution, Main Memory dynamically holds active programs, their instructions, and associated operands, ensuring seamless and efficient computing by allowing the CPU to retrieve and process information with minimal latency.<SEP>Main Memory is the primary data storage component directly accessible by the CPU.<SEP>Main memory refers to the primary storage of a computer system used for active data and program execution.

Addressing
Addressing is the process of assigning unique addresses to storage cells to enable access and retrieval of data.

MAR
MAR (Memory Address Register) is a register in the CPU that holds the address of the memory location to be accessed.

Memory Access
Memory access refers to the process of reading from or writing to a specific memory location during instruction execution.

Dead Time
Dead time refers to the period during concentrated refresh when the memory is inaccessible for read/write operations.

Word Addressing
Word addressing is a method of organizing memory where entire words are assigned a single address.

Column Address
In DRAM, the column address is used to select a specific column within a selected row for data access.

Distributed Refresh
Distributed refresh divides the memory cycle into two parts: one for normal access and one for refresh, avoiding dead time but increasing total access time.

Asynchronous Refresh
Asynchronous refresh spreads refresh requests across the refresh cycle by refreshing one row at a time at regular intervals, minimizing idle wait periods for the CPU.

Memory Chip
A memory chip is a physical integrated circuit that contains DRAM cells and support circuitry for data storage and access.

Bit Price
Bit price refers to the cost per bit of memory, which is lower in DRAM compared to SRAM due to higher integration density.<SEP>Bit price is the cost per bit, calculated as total cost divided by total storage capacity.

Address Pin Multiplexing
Address pin multiplexing is a technique that reduces the number of address pins by inputting row and column addresses sequentially via the same set of pins.

Row Address
In DRAM, the row address is used to select a specific row of memory cells for refresh or access.

CPU
The CPU (Central Processing Unit) is the primary processor in a computer system responsible for executing instructions and managing data flow between components. As the central processing unit, it serves as the core component of a computer, handling the execution of instructions and the processing of data. The CPU interacts with memory systems and is tasked with managing timing associated with memory refresh operations, ensuring efficient and accurate data handling. It operates at a significantly faster speed compared to memory, enabling it to efficiently process multiple instructions fetched simultaneously. This high-speed operation allows the CPU to maintain optimal performance by minimizing bottlenecks in data processing. Additionally, the CPU is responsible for controlling the selection of memory chips and accessing specific memory cells, playing a pivotal role in data retrieval and storage coordination. Overall, the CPU orchestrates critical operations within a computer, managing instruction execution, data processing, memory access, and system component communication, thereby acting as the central intelligence of the computing system.<SEP>CPU is the central processing unit that performs most of the processing inside a computer and interacts with main memory via buses.<SEP>CPU is the central processing unit that issues read and write requests for memory access.<SEP>CPU (Central Processing Unit) is the primary processor of a computer system responsible for executing instructions.<SEP>CPU is the central processing unit responsible for executing instructions and accessing memory.

Read/Write Control Circuit
The read/write control circuit in main memory manages read and write operations based on control signals from the CPU.

Address Decoder
The address decoder in main memory interprets the address signal and selects the appropriate memory cell.<SEP>Address decoder is a circuit that generates chip select signals from high-order address lines.

Address Bus
The address bus is a set of lines used to transfer the memory address from the CPU to the main memory.<SEP>Address bus is a communication pathway that carries memory addresses from the CPU to main memory, determining the maximum addressable memory space.

Read-After-Write Regeneration
Read-after-write regeneration is the process of rewriting data to a memory cell immediately after a read operation to preserve its state.

MDR
MDR (Memory Data Register) is a register in the CPU that holds the data being transferred to or from memory.

Storage Word Length
Storage word length refers to the number of bits contained in a single memory word, typically matching the data bus width.

Data Bus
The data bus is a set of lines used to transfer data between the CPU and the main memory.<SEP>Data bus is a communication pathway that transfers data between the CPU and main memory, with its width and frequency affecting data transfer rate.

Destructive Readout
Destructive readout is a characteristic of DRAM where reading data from a cell destroys the stored charge, requiring regeneration.<SEP>Destructive Readout occurs when reading a memory cell destroys the original stored information, requiring a regeneration operation immediately after read.<SEP>Destructive readout is a type of memory access where data is lost during reading and must be regenerated immediately.

100m Sprint Record
The 100m sprint record is a benchmark in athletics, recently broken by Noah Carter.

64-Bit Data Bus
A 64-bit data bus is a data transfer path capable of moving 64 bits of data simultaneously, increasing data throughput.

Addressable Memory Space
Addressable memory space is the total range of memory addresses that can be accessed by the CPU, determined by the number of address lines.

36-Bit Address Bus
A 36-bit address bus allows the CPU to access up to 2^36 unique memory addresses, forming the maximum addressable memory space.

Power Supply
The power supply provides continuous electrical energy to the DRAM, though data is lost if power is omitted due to charge leakage.

Binary Representation
Each storage cell has two stable states to represent the binary values 0 and 1.

Noah Carter
Noah Carter set a new 100m sprint record at the championship.

Tokyo
The World Athletics Championship is being hosted in Tokyo.

World Athletics Championship
The World Athletics Championship is being hosted in Tokyo.

Cache
Cache is a high-speed memory layer that stores copies of frequently accessed data from main memory to reduce access time and improve overall system performance. Positioned close to the processor, typically implemented using SRAM (Static Random-Access Memory) chips, Cache serves as a small-capacity but fast intermediary between the CPU and main memory. By temporarily holding data currently being used by the CPU or data that is likely to be accessed next, Cache minimizes the latency associated with retrieving information from slower main memory. This mechanism enhances system efficiency by drastically reducing the time required for data access, especially in operations involving repeated or sequential data retrieval. Cache operates on the principle of data locality, where recently or frequently accessed data is kept readily available, further optimizing computational throughput. As a critical component in modern computing architectures, Cache plays a vital role in maintaining high-speed data access and improving the responsiveness of processing systems.<SEP>Cache is a high-speed memory that stores copies of frequently accessed data from main memory to reduce access time.<SEP>Cache is a high-speed memory that stores copies of data from frequently used main memory locations to reduce access time.<SEP>Cache is a high-speed memory that stores copies of data from main memory to improve access speed.<SEP>Cache is a high-speed memory component located between CPU and main memory to reduce data access latency.<SEP>Cache refers to a fast memory layer that stores frequently accessed data to improve system performance; virtual memory employs similar principles.

Virtual Storage System
A system that allows programmers to use an address space larger than the physical main memory by using a combination of main memory and disk storage.<SEP>A memory management system that uses virtual addressing to provide processes with the illusion of contiguous memory.

Multi-Level Storage System
A storage system architecture designed to resolve the conflict between high capacity, fast speed, and low cost in computer systems by using hierarchical memory layers.

Hardware
The physical components responsible for managing data movement between cache and main memory automatically.<SEP>Hardware refers to physical components of the computer system that implement cache and part of virtual memory.<SEP>Hardware refers to physical components such as the CPU, memory, and controllers that support system operations.

Storage Hierarchy Structure
The primary design principle of the multi-level storage system where each upper-level storage acts as a high-speed cache for the lower-level storage.

Disk Storage
Disk storage, also known as auxiliary storage, is a non-volatile storage medium used for long-term data retention with large capacity.

Operating System
The software layer that manages the interaction between hardware and application programs, particularly in data transfer between main memory and disk storage.<SEP>The operating system manages memory resources, implements virtual memory, and coordinates between hardware and software.<SEP>The operating system manages memory and handles page faults by loading missing pages into main memory.

Address Space
The range of memory addresses available to a programmer in a virtual storage system, which can exceed the physical capacity of main memory.<SEP>Address space refers to the total range of addresses available for memory access.

Main Memory- Auxiliary Storage Layer
A hierarchical storage layer that increases system capacity by using auxiliary storage as an extension of main memory.

Data Transfer
The process of moving data from one storage level to another, such as from disk to main memory or main memory to cache.

Programmer
A person who writes software and programs, whose view of address space is abstracted by the virtual storage system.

Cache- Main Memory Layer
A hierarchical storage layer that resolves the speed mismatch between CPU and main memory by using cache as a high-speed buffer.

Capacity Expansion Solution
This layer addresses storage capacity limitations by allowing data to be swapped between main memory and auxiliary storage, managed by hardware and the operating system in a transparent way to application programmers.

Speed-Matching Solution
This layer resolves the speed mismatch between the CPU and main memory through hardware-managed data transfers that are transparent to programmers.

TLB
TLB (Translation Lookaside Buffer) is a cache used to speed up virtual address translation by storing recent virtual-to-physical address mappings.<SEP>TLB (Translation Lookaside Buffer) is a hardware component that caches page table entries to speed up virtual address translation.<SEP>TLB is a translation lookaside buffer that stores recent translations of virtual page numbers to physical page numbers, improving memory access speed.

Page Table Index
Page Table Index is the part of a virtual page number used to index the page table entry in a two-level page table system.

Full Associative TLB
Full Associative TLB is a TLB design where any virtual page can be stored in any TLB entry, allowing maximum flexibility in address matching.

Page Directory Index
Page Directory Index is the part of a virtual page number used to index the page directory in a two-level page table system.

2 Way Set Associative Cache
2 Way Set Associative Cache is a cache mapping technique where each memory block can be stored in one of two possible cache lines within a set.

32 Bit Virtual Address
32 Bit Virtual Address is a 32-bit address issued by the CPU for accessing virtual memory.

Virtual Page Number
Virtual Page Number is the portion of a virtual address used to index into the page table or TLB.<SEP>Virtual Page Number is the part of a virtual address that identifies the page within a virtual address space.<SEP>The high-order field of a virtual address that identifies the virtual page.<SEP>Virtual Page Number is the identifier for a page in virtual memory that is translated to a physical page number via the TLB or page table.

Page Table
Page Table is a data structure used by the operating system to store the mapping between virtual and physical page numbers.<SEP>Page table is a data structure that keeps track of the mapping between virtual pages and physical pages in memory.<SEP>Page Table is a data structure stored in main memory that maps virtual pages to physical frames.<SEP>A page table is a data structure stored in main memory that maps virtual page numbers to physical page numbers.<SEP>Page Table is a data structure used by the operating system to store mappings from virtual page numbers to physical page numbers, accessed during TLB misses.

Virtual Memory
Virtual Memory is a memory management technique that allows a computer to use more memory than physically available by combining RAM and disk storage.<SEP>Virtual memory is a memory management technique that provides an illusion of a large main memory by using secondary storage, improving system performance by handling larger programs than physical memory can hold.<SEP>Virtual memory is a memory management technique that creates a large, unified address space by combining main memory and secondary storage, allowing users to program without regard to actual physical memory size or location.

Replacement Policy
Replacement Policy is a strategy used to determine which cache entry to evict when the cache is full and a new entry must be stored.

Physical Address
Physical Address is the actual address in main memory that corresponds to a virtual address after translation.<SEP>A physical address is the actual location in main memory where data or instructions are stored, derived from a virtual address through address translation.<SEP>A physical address is the real memory location in main memory, also known as an actual address.

Block Offset
Block Offset is the portion of an address used to select a specific byte within a cache block.

Cache Line
Cache Line is a unit of data storage in cache memory that holds a block of data from main memory.<SEP>Cache Line is a single unit of storage within a cache that holds a block of data from main memory.<SEP>Cache Line is another term for Cache Block, referring to a unit of data in Cache that holds a fixed number of bytes.<SEP>Cache line is a unit of data transfer between main memory and cache, typically containing a block of data.

Tag Field
Tag Field is a portion of a memory address stored in cache to identify which main memory block is stored in the cache line.

Time Locality
Time locality indicates that information recently used is likely to be used again in the near future, due to program structures such as loops, repeated subroutine segments, and array access patterns.

Spatial Locality
Spatial locality indicates that information near the currently accessed data is likely to be accessed soon, due to sequential instruction execution and data storage in clusters such as vectors and arrays.<SEP>Spatial Locality refers to the tendency of programs to access memory locations that are close to each other, which is exploited by write allocation strategies.

High-Speed Buffering Technology
High-Speed Buffering Technology leverages the principle of locality to store frequently accessed data in a fast, small-capacity cache, enabling CPU operations to primarily target the cache to improve execution speed.

Program Access Locality Principle
The Program Access Locality Principle refers to the tendency of programs to access a relatively small portion of their address space intensively over a short period, encompassing both temporal and spatial locality.

Page-Based Virtual Memory
Page-based virtual memory is a memory management method that uses pages as the basic unit for allocating and managing virtual and physical memory.

Physical Page
Physical page, also known as real page or page frame, refers to a block of memory in main memory that is used to store data from virtual memory.

Page Size
Page size is the fixed size of each page in both virtual and physical memory, ensuring consistent alignment.

Virtual Page
Virtual page, also known asè™šé¡µ, is a block of memory in the virtual address space that is mapped to physical memory.

Virtual Address Space
Virtual address space is the memory space available to a process, divided into virtual pages.

Structural Simplicity
Structural simplicity refers to the reduced complexity in the design and layout of memory components, contributing to higher bit density.

Non-Volatile
Non-volatile refers to the property of retaining stored data even when power is lost.

ROM
ROM is a type of read-only memory that retains data even after power loss and is non-volatile.<SEP>ROM (Read-Only Memory) is a non-volatile memory type used to store permanent data such as system firmware and boot instructions.

Random Access
Random access is a method of accessing data in memory where any location can be directly accessed without sequential access.

Bit Density
Bit density refers to the number of data bits stored per unit area in a memory device, often used to measure storage efficiency.

RAM
RAM is a volatile memory that loses data when power is turned off and supports random access.<SEP>RAM (Random Access Memory) is a type of volatile memory used for temporary storage during program execution and user data processing.

Volatile
SRAM is volatile and loses its stored data when power is turned off.

Full Associative Mapping
Full Associative Mapping is a TLB mapping technique where any page table entry can be stored in any TLB set.<SEP>Full Associative Mapping is a cache mapping technique where any block from main memory can be placed in any line of the cache.<SEP>Full associative mapping allows any virtual page to be stored in any available physical page frame, enhancing flexibility and hit rates.

Locality Principle
Locality Principle is the concept that programs tend to access the same set of memory locations repeatedly over a short period.<SEP>The locality principle refers to the tendency of programs to access a limited set of memory locations repeatedly, forming the basis for cache and virtual memory optimizations.<SEP>Locality Principle refers to the tendency of a processor to access the same set of memory locations repeatedly over a short period of time.

Virtual Address Translation
Virtual Address Translation is the process of converting virtual addresses to physical addresses during memory access.

Set Associative Mapping
Set Associative Mapping is a TLB mapping technique where each page table entry is stored in a specific set, determined by a portion of the virtual page number.<SEP>Set Associative Mapping is a cache mapping technique that divides the cache into sets, where a block from main memory can be placed in any line within a specific set.<SEP>Set associative mapping divides the cache into groups (sets), with each block assigned to a specific set, and can be placed in any line within that set.

Slow Table
Slow Table refers to the page table stored in main memory, in contrast to the fast TLB, and is used as a backup during page table lookups.

TLB Entry
TLB Entry is a unit in the TLB that stores a virtual page number and its corresponding physical page frame.

TLB Tag
TLB Tag is a field in a TLB entry used to identify the corresponding virtual page number.

Speed
Speed is the rate at which data can be accessed or processed, a critical attribute in determining system performance for both cache and virtual memory.

System Performance
System performance refers to the efficiency and speed of a computer system in executing tasks, influenced by memory hierarchy and data access mechanisms.

Information Block
An information block is a unit of data that is moved between memory levels, used as the basic exchange unit in virtual memory and cache systems.

Address Mapping
Address mapping is the process of translating logical addresses to physical addresses, a shared concern in both cache and virtual memory systems.

Price
Price refers to the cost of memory components, forming a gradient along with capacity and speed in memory systems.

Capacity
Capacity refers to the amount of data that can be stored in a memory system, a key factor in both virtual memory and cache.

Replacement Algorithm
A replacement algorithm determines which data to evict from memory when new data must be loaded, used in both cache and virtual memory operations.<SEP>A Replacement Algorithm determines which cache line should be replaced when a new block is to be loaded into a full cache.<SEP>Replacement Algorithm is a strategy used to determine which block in the Cache should be replaced when the Cache is full and a new block needs to be loaded.<SEP>A replacement algorithm is used to determine which page or segment to remove from main memory when it is full and a new one needs to be loaded.

Fast Cache
Fast cache is a design concept based on locality, placing active data in faster memory components to reduce access latency.

Secondary Storage
Secondary storage, such as hard drives, is used for long-term data storage and provides backing for virtual memory.<SEP>Secondary storage is non-volatile memory used for long-term data storage, such as hard drives or SSDs.

Cache Hierarchy
The cache hierarchy refers to the layered arrangement of cache levels in a system, from L1 to L2, aimed at improving memory access speed.

Update Strategy
An update strategy defines how changes to data in memory are synchronized, a common issue in both cache and virtual memory systems.

Virtual Memory System
A virtual memory system extends physical memory through secondary storage, enabling efficient use of limited RAM.

Programmer Transparency
Programmer transparency refers to the extent to which memory mechanisms are hidden from programmers, varying between cache (transparent) and virtual memory (partially visible).

Page Fault
A page fault occurs when requested data is not in main memory and must be loaded from secondary storage in a virtual memory system.<SEP>A condition that occurs when a requested virtual page is not present in main memory, requiring the operating system to handle page loading.

Cache Miss
A cache miss occurs when requested data is not found in the cache and must be retrieved from slower memory.<SEP>Cache miss occurs when the requested data block is not found in the cache, requiring a fetch from main memory.<SEP>Cache Miss occurs when the requested data is not in the Cache, requiring access to Main Memory.

Page Offset
The low-order field of a virtual address or physical address that represents the position within a page.

Physical Page Number
The high-order field of a physical address that identifies the physical page in main memory.<SEP>Physical Page Number is the actual address in main memory corresponding to a virtual page number after translation.

Virtual Address
A virtual address is an address generated by the CPU that must be converted to a physical address for memory access in a virtual storage system.<SEP>A virtual address is an address used by a program to access memory, which is translated into a physical address by the memory management unit.

Page Table Base Register
A register that stores the starting address of the page table for a given process.

Process
A process is an instance of a program in execution, each having its own page table and virtual address space.

Standard Subroutine
Standard subroutines are reusable sets of instructions stored in ROM for common operations in computing systems.

Storage Chip
A storage chip is a semiconductor device used in computer memory systems, available in types such as RAM and ROM, and is essential for storing data and instructions.<SEP>Storage chip is a memory component that requires chip selection and word selection for data read/write operations.

Chip Select Control Line
The chip select control line (CS) is a signal used to enable or disable a specific storage chip, allowing the CPU to select a particular chip during memory access.

System Program
System programs are low-level software routines stored in ROM for initializing and managing system functions.

Data Line
The data line is a signal line used for transmitting data between the CPU and memory components, with bit-width determining data transfer capacity.

Address Line
The address line is a signal line used to specify the memory location or address of a data unit within a storage device or system.

Read/Write Control Line
The read/write control line is a signal used to determine the direction of data transfer between the CPU and memory, enabling read or write operations.

Constant Value
Constant values are fixed data elements stored in ROM for use in program execution.

Memory Expansion
Memory expansion refers to the process of increasing the total storage capacity of a system by adding additional storage chips.

Chip Interior Logic
Chip interior logic is the internal circuitry within a storage chip responsible for decoding address lines and selecting specific memory cells.

External Decoder Logic
External decoder logic is a circuit external to storage chips used to decode high-order address lines for chip selection.

Memory Access Request
A memory access request is a signal initiated by the CPU to read from or write to a memory location.

MREQ
MREQ (Memory Request) is a control signal generated by the CPU indicating a request for memory access, typically active-low.

MROM
MROM is a type of ROM where data is permanently written during the semiconductor manufacturing process, making it unchangeable after production.

PROM
PROM is a type of ROM that allows a single programming session by the user using a programmer, after which the data cannot be altered.

EPROM
EPROM is a type of ROM that can be programmed and erased multiple times using ultraviolet light, enabling revisions to stored data.

SSD
SSD, or Solid State Drive, is a storage device based on flash memory that uses a chip array for data storage and offers high-speed read/write operations.

Semiconductor Manufacturing Process
The semiconductor manufacturing process is the production method used by vendors to embed data directly into MROM chips.

Ultraviolet Erasure
Ultraviolet erasure is a method used to erase data from EPROM by exposing the chip to UV light.

Programming
Programming is the process of writing data into PROM or EPROM using a specialized programmer device.

Flash Memory
Flash Memory is a type of non-volatile memory derived from EPROM, capable of fast electric erasure and reprogramming without power.<SEP>Flash memory is the core storage component in SSDs with a limited number of program/erase cycles, typically ranging from hundreds to thousands.

Electric Erasure
Electric erasure is the method used in Flash memory to erase and rewrite data electronically, without requiring UV light.

Integration Density
Integration density describes the number of components or circuits packed into a given area of a semiconductor chip, influencing performance and cost.

Cost Efficiency
Cost efficiency is a measure of how economical a technology is in terms of price relative to performance and capacity.

Power Consumption
Power consumption refers to the amount of electrical energy used by a device during operation, a key consideration in portable systems.

Write Speed
Write speed refers to the rate at which data can be written or rewritten onto a storage device, a factor affecting usability.

Non-Volatile Storage
Non-volatile storage refers to the ability of memory devices to retain data even when power is removed.

TLB Miss
TLB miss occurs when the requested virtual page number is not found in the TLB, requiring a page table lookup.

Page
Page refers to a fixed-size block of memory used in virtual memory systems, which may reside in main memory or on disk.<SEP>A page is the smallest unit of data that can be read or written in flash memory, typically sized between 512B and 4KB.<SEP>A page is a fixed-size block of memory used in virtual memory management for transferring data between main memory and secondary storage.

Page Miss
Page miss, or page fault, occurs when the requested page is not present in main memory, requiring loading from disk.

Disk
Disk refers to secondary storage, such as a hard drive or SSD, used for long-term data storage.<SEP>Disk is a mechanical storage device that stores data using magnetic surfaces, organized into tracks, surfaces, and sectors.

Multilevel Storage System
Multilevel storage system refers to a hierarchy of storage mechanisms including TLB, Cache, main memory, and disk, designed to optimize access speed and capacity.

Page Fault Handling
Page fault handling is a software-based process executed by the operating system when a page miss occurs, involving loading the page from disk.

Software
Software refers to programs and instructions, such as the operating system, that manage system resources and processes.

TLB Replacement
TLB replacement refers to the algorithm or strategy used to manage TLB entries when a miss occurs, which can be handled by hardware or software.

CPU Memory Access
CPU Memory Access refers to the process by which the CPU requests data from memory, potentially triggering TLB, Cache, and Page lookups.<SEP>CPU memory access refers to the process of retrieving data by the CPU, involving cache checking and main memory access if necessary.

Multi-Module Memory
Multi-module memory is a spatial parallel technology that enhances memory throughput by enabling parallel operation of multiple identical storage modules.

Multi-Body Interleaved Memory
Multi-body interleaved memory consists of multiple storage modules with identical capacity and access speed, each having independent read/write control circuits, address registers, and data registers, enabling both parallel and interleaved operation.

Memory Throughput
Memory throughput refers to the rate at which data can be read from or written to memory, enhanced through parallel module operation.

Single-Body Multi-Word Memory
Single-body multi-word memory stores m words per storage unit with a bus width of m words, allowing m words to be read in parallel in one access cycle.

Instruction Fetching
Instruction fetching is the process of retrieving instructions from main memory to the CPU for execution.

Transfer Instruction
A transfer instruction is a type of command that alters the flow of execution, potentially disrupting continuous data access.

Access Cycle
An access cycle is the time required to complete one memory access operation, with instructions retrieved every 1/m of a cycle in single-body multi-word systems.<SEP>Access cycle is the minimum time interval required between two consecutive independent memory operations (read or write).

Continuous Data Storage
Continuous data storage refers to the arrangement of data in consecutive memory locations, which is necessary for optimal performance in single-body multi-word systems.

Multi-Body Parallel Memory
Multi-body parallel memory is another term for multi-body interleaved memory, referring to a storage architecture where multiple modules operate in parallel to enhance performance.

Independent Read/Write Control Circuits
Independent read/write control circuits are components within each storage module enabling autonomous operation.

Data Register
A data register holds the data being transferred between the memory module and the CPU.

Address Register
An address register stores the memory address for the current read or write operation.

Chip Select
Chip select is the process of choosing a specific memory chip for data access.

Decoder-Based Chip Selection
Decoder-based chip selection uses an address decoder to generate chip select signals from high-order address lines.

Address Assignment
Address assignment refers to the process of allocating specific addresses to memory cells for data access.

Word Select
Word select is the process of selecting a specific storage unit within a targeted memory chip.

Line Selection Method
Line selection method uses high-order address lines directly connected to the chip select pins; a "0" on a line selects the corresponding chip.

High-Order Address Lines
High-order address lines are used for chip selection and are not used for addressing within the chip.

Dynamic Random Access Memory
Dynamic Random Access Memory is a type of volatile memory that requires periodic refreshing to maintain stored data.

DRAM Chip
DRAM Chip is a type of dynamic random access memory used in main memory.

Static Random Access Memory
Static Random Access Memory is a type of volatile memory that retains data as long as power is supplied.

Read-Only Memory
Read-Only Memory is a category of non-volatile memory that stores data permanently.<SEP>Read-Only Memory (ROM) allows data to be read but not written; information stored remains intact even after power loss and is used for fixed programs, constants, and lookup tables.

SRAM Chip
SRAM Chip is a type of static random access memory used in cache memory close to the processor.

Random Access Memory
Random Access Memory is a category of volatile memory that allows data to be read and written in any order.<SEP>Random Access Memory (RAM) allows random access to any storage unit regardless of physical location, offering fast read/write capabilities; it is commonly used for main memory and cache.

Volatile Memory
Volatile Memory is a type of memory that loses stored data when power is turned off.<SEP>Volatile Memory loses stored data when power is removed; examples include RAM.

Non-Volatile Memory
Non-Volatile Memory retains stored data even after power is turned off.<SEP>Non-Volatile Memory retains stored data even after power loss; examples include ROM, magnetic surface storage, and optical storage.

Memory Module
Memory module is a circuit board containing multiple memory chips, used to expand the main memory of a computer system.

ROM Chip
ROM chip is a type of non-volatile memory on the motherboard that stores firmware and system startup instructions.

Memory Chip Extension Technology
Memory chip extension technology is a technique used to combine multiple memory chips into a single memory module to increase storage capacity.

Control Bus
Control bus manages the flow of signals between the CPU and main memory, indicating read/write operations and timing of data transfers.

Direct Mapping
Direct Mapping is a cache mapping technique in which a block from main memory can be placed in only one specific cache line.<SEP>Direct mapping is a cache addressing method where each main memory block maps to exactly one cache line, determined by a modulo operation.

FIFO Algorithm
FIFO Algorithm is a replacement strategy that replaces the cache line that was loaded the earliest.

Total Bus Connection
Total bus connection refers to the combined interaction of data, address, and control buses linking the CPU with main memory.

Random Algorithm
Random Algorithm is a replacement strategy that randomly selects a cache line for replacement, without considering access patterns.

Single Chip Capacity Limitation
Single chip capacity limitation refers to the inherent physical constraint of individual memory chips, which restricts the amount of data they can store and necessitates the use of chip expansion techniques.

LRU Algorithm
LRU Algorithm is a replacement strategy that replaces the cache line that has not been accessed for the longest period, based on the principle of locality.

LFU Algorithm
LFU Algorithm is a replacement strategy that replaces the cache line with the lowest access frequency over a period of time.

LRU Replacement Bit
LRU Replacement Bit is a counter associated with each cache line in an LRU algorithm to track access history and determine replacement.

Counting Mechanism
Counting Mechanism is a method used in replacement algorithms to track access frequency or recency.

Thrashing
Thrashing is a phenomenon in memory systems where excessive page swapping or cache replacements degrade performance due to high contention.

Data Transfer Rate
The bit width and operating frequency of the data bus directly determine the data transfer rate.<SEP>Data transfer rate is the number of bits transferred per second, calculated as data width divided by access cycle time.

Main Memory Block
A Main Memory Block is a unit of data transferred between main memory and cache during memory operations.

Cache Line Replacement
Cache Line Replacement refers to the process of removing an existing cache line to make space for a new one when the cache is full.

Cache Group
Cache Group is a set of cache lines used in set-associative mapping, where a main memory block can be mapped to any line within the group.

Maximum Memory Space
The number of bits in the address bus defines the maximum memory space that can be addressed.

Count Value
Count Value is a numerical value that tracks usage frequency or recency in replacement algorithms.

Read/Write Operation
The control bus signals the type of operation and marks the completion of data input or output.

Non-Destructive Readout
Non-destructive readout is a read operation where data remains unchanged after being read, enabling SRAM to retain its original state.<SEP>Non-Destructive Readout allows reading a memory cell without destroying its stored content, preserving data integrity during access.

Six Transistor MOS
Six transistor MOS is a circuit configuration used in SRAM to implement bistable triggers for data storage.

Storage Unit
A storage unit is composed of multiple storage cells sharing the same address code.

High Access Speed
High access speed refers to the fast retrieval and storage of data, a key characteristic of SRAM.

Storage Body
A storage body is a collection of multiple storage units used in memory systems.

Bistable Trigger
A bistable trigger is a circuit with two stable states used to store binary information, commonly implemented using six MOS transistors in SRAM.

Low Integration Density
Low integration density means SRAM has fewer memory cells per unit area, limiting its scalability.

High Cost
High cost is a result of low integration density and complex circuitry in SRAM.

High Power Consumption
High power consumption is a drawback of SRAM due to constant current flow in the bistable trigger circuit.

Cache Memory
Cache memory is a high-speed memory used to store frequently accessed data, typically implemented using SRAM.<SEP>Cache Memory is located between the CPU and main memory, storing frequently used instructions and data to enable fast CPU access; it offers high-speed access matching CPU speed but has limited capacity and high price.

Cache Hit
Cache Hit occurs when the requested data is found in the Cache, allowing direct access without accessing Main Memory.

Block Length
Block Length, also known as Line Length, is the size of a Cache Block in bytes.

Cache Capacity
Cache Capacity refers to the total amount of data that the Cache can hold, which is significantly smaller than Main Memory capacity.

Cache Block
Cache Block, also known as Cache Line, is a unit of data transfer between Cache and Main Memory, consisting of multiple bytes.

Main Memory Capacity
Main Memory Capacity is the total storage size of the primary memory, which is much larger than Cache capacity.

Hardware Implementation
Hardware Implementation refers to the fact that all Cache operations are managed by dedicated hardware.

Write Policy
Write Policy defines how updates to data in the Cache are handled, with common methods being Write-Through and Write-Back.

Data Transfer Unit
Data Transfer Unit is the size of data transferred between components: bytes between CPU and Cache, and Cache Blocks between Cache and Main Memory.

Write-Through
Write-Through is a write policy where data is written simultaneously to both Cache and Main Memory.

Write-Back
Write-Back is a write policy where data is written only to Cache initially, and written back to Main Memory later when the block is replaced.<SEP>Write-back is a technique used in virtual memory systems to delay writing modified data to secondary storage until necessary, improving performance.

Solid State Drive
A Solid State Drive (SSD) is a storage device based on flash memory technology, featuring high performance, no moving parts, and improved reliability compared to traditional hard drives.<SEP>Solid State Drive (SSD) is a storage device that uses flash memory and has a limited write/erase endurance.

Flash Translation Layer
The flash translation layer translates logical block read/write requests from the CPU into physical read/write signals for the flash memory, acting as a substitute for the disk controller.

Block
A block is a unit of memory in flash memory that consists of multiple pages and is used for data erasure operations in SSDs.<SEP>Block is a segment of data in main memory that is mapped to a cache line.

Mechanical Hard Disk
A mechanical hard disk uses spinning platters and moving read/write heads, in contrast to the solid-state nature of SSDs.

Flash Memory Chip
A flash memory chip is a core component of an SSD, used for storing data and replacing mechanical drive components found in traditional hard disks.

Data Erasure
Data erasure in SSDs is performed at the block level and requires the entire block to be erased before new data can be written.

Random Write Operation
A random write operation in SSDs is slow due to the need to copy valid data from a block to a new block before rewriting, which involves block-level erasure and page migration.

Flash Memory Technology
Flash memory technology enables non-volatile data storage and is the foundation of SSD operation, allowing data retention without power.

Energy Efficiency
Energy efficiency in SSDs results from the lack of mechanical components, reducing power consumption compared to traditional hard drives.

Ssd Performance
SSD performance includes fast random access times, low latency, and high data throughput due to the absence of moving parts.

Price Trend
The price trend of SSDs shows a continual decline with technological advancement, making them more accessible over time.

Data Security
Data security is enhanced in SSDs because they have no moving components and are less prone to mechanical failure.<SEP>Data security refers to the protection of data from loss or corruption, enhanced by redundancy and parity in RAID.

Vibration Resistance
Vibration resistance is a characteristic of SSDs due to their solid-state design, making them less susceptible to physical damage from shocks.

Mechanical Hard Disk Controller
The flash translation layer performs the role of a disk controller in traditional hard disks by managing data access requests.

Optical Storage
Optical Storage refers to memory using optical discs for data storage, such as CD and DVD.

Magnetic Core Memory
Magnetic Core Memory is an early type of memory that uses magnetic cores to store data.

Semiconductor Memory
Semiconductor Memory includes MOS-type and bipolar-type memory, fabricated using semiconductor materials for data storage.

Auxiliary Memory
Auxiliary Memory, also called secondary memory or external memory, stores data and programs not currently in use and information requiring permanent storage; it has large capacity, slower access speed, and lower cost per unit.

Magnetic Surface Storage
Magnetic Surface Storage includes magnetic disks and tapes, using magnetic media to store data.

Static RAM
Static RAM is a type of RAM that maintains data as long as power is supplied and does not require refreshing.

Serial Access Storage
Serial Access Storage requires data to be accessed in a sequential or predetermined physical order, including sequential and direct access types such as magnetic tape and disk.

Direct Access Storage
Direct Access Storage enables access to specific data locations by first finding a general region (e.g., disk track) and then searching within it, combining features of sequential and random access.

Dynamic RAM
Dynamic RAM is a type of RAM that must be periodically refreshed to maintain stored data and is more space-efficient than static RAM.

Sequential Access Storage
Sequential Access Storage allows data access only in a deterministic physical order, with access times dependent on location; it is slow and used for large data archives.

Memory System
Destructive readout necessitates regeneration after reading, requiring immediate refresh to maintain data integrity.

Dirty Bit
A Dirty Bit is a flag in each Cache line indicating whether the corresponding block has been modified and needs to be written back to main memory upon replacement.

Write Hit
Write Hit occurs when a write operation targets a Cache block that is already present, triggering specific write strategies to maintain consistency between Cache and main memory.

Cache Consistency Problem
The Cache consistency problem arises because Cache content is a copy of main memory blocks, requiring strategies to maintain data synchronization when Cache is updated.

Write Through
Write Through, also known as Write-Through, is a write strategy where data is written simultaneously to Cache and main memory upon a write hit.

Write Allocate
Write Allocate, also known as Write Allocation, is a strategy where a miss in a write operation loads the corresponding block into Cache before performing the write.

Not-Write-Allocate
Not-Write-Allocate is a strategy where a write miss updates main memory only without loading the block into Cache.

Write Buffer
A Write Buffer is a FIFO queue placed between Cache and main memory to reduce the latency of direct main memory writes in Write Through mode.

Write Back
Write Back is a write strategy where data is written only to Cache on a write hit, and main memory is updated only when the block is replaced.

Separate Cache Structure
Separate Cache Structure refers to the design of independent instruction and data caches to avoid resource conflicts and improve performance.

Data Cache
Data Cache is a dedicated cache for storing frequently accessed data to speed up data read and write operations.

L1 Cache
L1 Cache is the first-level cache closest to the CPU, offering the fastest access speed but limited capacity.

Memory Access Conflict
Memory Access Conflict arises in unified Cache systems when instruction fetch and data access compete for the same Cache resources.

Cache Write Strategy
Cache Write Strategy refers to the decision-making process for handling write operations based on hit/miss conditions and system design.

L2 Cache
L2 Cache is the second-level cache, further from the CPU than L1 Cache, with slower access speed but larger capacity.

Instruction Cache
Instruction Cache is a dedicated cache for storing frequently accessed instructions to improve instruction fetch efficiency.

Performance Optimization
Performance Optimization in caching involves leveraging architectural features like separate caches and multi-level hierarchies to improve system efficiency.

RAID2
RAID2 is a disk array configuration that uses Hamming code error correction for data redundancy, requiring multiple disks and specialized hardware.

RAID4
RAID4 is a disk array configuration that uses block-level striping with a dedicated parity disk for fault tolerance.

RAID3
RAID3 is a disk array configuration that uses byte-level striping with dedicated parity, enabling fault tolerance and sequential data access.

RAID1
RAID1 is a disk array configuration that uses mirroring, duplicating data across two drives for redundancy and fault tolerance.

Physical Disk
A physical disk is an individual hardware component used in RAID configurations to store data.

RAID
RAID (Redundant Array of Independent Disks) is a data storage technology that combines multiple physical disks into a single logical unit to improve performance, reliability, and data safety.

RAID5
RAID5 is a disk array configuration that uses block-level striping with distributed parity, providing fault tolerance and efficient use of storage space.

RAID0
RAID0 is a disk array configuration that uses striping without redundancy or parity, providing high performance and increased storage capacity but no fault tolerance.

Logical Disk
A logical disk is a virtual disk unit created by combining multiple physical disks in a RAID setup.

Data Striping
Data striping is the process of dividing data into blocks and distributing them across multiple disks for parallel access and improved performance.

Mirroring
Mirroring is a data redundancy technique where data is duplicated across multiple disks in RAID1 to ensure availability upon failure.

Fault Tolerance
Fault tolerance is the ability of a storage system to continue operating despite the failure of one or more disks.

Storage Performance
Storage performance describes the speed and efficiency of data read/write operations in a RAID system.

Parity
Parity is a mechanism used in RAID to provide fault tolerance by storing redundant data for error detection and recovery.

Data Recovery
Data recovery refers to the process of retrieving data from a failed disk in a RAID system, enabled by redundancy or parity.

Independent Redundant Disk Array
Independent Redundant Disk Array is the full form of RAID, referring to the technology that combines multiple physical disks into a single logical unit for enhanced performance and reliability.

Tag
Tag is a field in a cache line that stores the higher-order bits of the main memory address to identify which block it contains.

Valid Bit
Valid bit is a flag in a cache line indicating whether the data in the line is valid (i.e., a valid copy of a main memory block).

Fully Associative Mapping
Fully associative mapping allows any main memory block to be placed in any cache line, requiring comparison of all tags during access.

Miss
Miss occurs when requested data is not found in the cache, requiring a read from main memory.

Hit
Hit occurs when requested data is found in the cache, resulting in faster access than from main memory.

Cache Line Number
Cache line number is computed using the formula: main memory block number modulo total cache lines.

Block Conflict
Block conflict occurs when a block needs to be loaded into a cache line that is already occupied and cannot be replaced.

Main Memory Block Number
Main memory block number is the identifier for a block in main memory, used for mapping to cache.

Block inclusion refers to the principle that every block in a lower-level cache (e.g., L1) must also be present in a higher-level cache (e.g., L2) if it is part of the address hierarchy.

2-Way Set Associative
2-Way set associative mapping refers to a configuration where each cache set contains two cache lines, allowing flexibility in block placement within the set.

Address Tag Field
Address tag field is the portion of the main memory address used to match against the tag in a cache line during a memory access.

Data Distribution Discreteness
Data Distribution Discreteness describes the scattered or non-uniform distribution of data within memory.

Program Transfer Probability
Program Transfer Probability refers to the likelihood of program execution transferring between different sections of memory.

High-Speed Buffer Memory
High-Speed Buffer Memory is a component designed to improve data access speed in computing systems.

Parallel Main Memory System
Parallel Main Memory System is a memory architecture that uses multiple memory modules to improve data throughput.

Memory System Efficiency
Memory System Efficiency refers to the performance and speed with which a memory system delivers data to the CPU.

Static Wear Leveling
Static Wear Leveling is an advanced wear leveling method that redistributes data even in the absence of writes, to balance usage across all flash blocks.

Program/Erase Cycles
Program/Erase Cycles refer to the number of times a flash memory cell can be written to and erased before it fails.

Data Write Concentration
Data Write Concentration is the phenomenon where data writes are unevenly distributed across flash memory blocks, leading to early failure of certain blocks.

Dynamic Wear Leveling
Dynamic Wear Leveling is a wear leveling technique that prioritizes writing data to flash blocks with fewer erase cycles.

256GB SSD
A 256GB SSD is a solid-state drive with a total storage capacity of 256 gigabytes, commonly used in consumer and enterprise systems.

Wear Leveling
Wear Leveling is a technology used in SSDs to distribute write and erase cycles evenly across flash memory blocks to prevent premature failure.

Flash Memory Block
A Flash Memory Block is a unit of storage in flash memory that is erased and written in bulk and is subject to wear over time.

Lifetime of SSD
The lifetime of an SSD is determined by the endurance of its flash memory, with proper wear leveling significantly extending usable life.

Storage Speed
Storage speed indicates how quickly data can be transferred to or from the storage device, measured by data transfer rate.

Unit Cost
Unit cost represents the cost per bit of storage, calculated as total cost divided by total storage capacity.

Main Memory Bandwidth
Main memory bandwidth, also known as data transfer rate, measures the maximum amount of information that can be transferred from main memory per second, expressed in words/second, bytes/second, or bits/second.

Storage Capacity
Storage capacity refers to the total amount of data that a storage device can hold, calculated as the product of the number of storage words and the word length.

Access Time
Access time is the duration from initiating a memory operation to its completion, including read and write times.

Byte
Byte is a unit of digital information equal to 8 bits.

Bit
Bit is the smallest unit of digital information, representing a binary digit.

Word Length
Word length refers to the amount of data that can be accessed in a single operation.

Restoration Time
Restoration time is the period required for a memory device to recover its internal state after a read or write operation.

Storage Word Count
Storage word count defines the size of the address space of a storage device.

Disk address refers to the unique identifier used by the host to locate data on a disk, consisting of cylinder (track) number, disk surface (head) number, and sector number.

Disk Surface Head Number (4 Bits)

Cylinder Track Number (8 Bits)

16-Bit Binary Code

Sector Number (4 Bits)

Sector Number
Sector number identifies the specific sector within a track on a disk surface, used in disk addressing.

Disk Controller

Seek Operation
Seek operation is a disk function that moves the disk head to the correct track (cylinder) for data access, executed as a sequential phase.

Mechanical Disk
Mechanical disk is a physical storage device with moving parts, such as rotating platters and read/write heads, which perform serial operations.

Disk Access Process
Disk access process refers to the sequential steps involved in disk operations, starting with loading a control word followed by executing it.

Read Operation
Read operation is a disk function that retrieves data from a specific sector on a disk, performed sequentially.

Control Word
Control word is a command sent to the disk controller that specifies the type of operation (e.g., read, write, seek) and its parameters.

Write Operation
Write operation is a disk function that stores data into a specific sector on a disk, performed sequentially.
